ence was splitpaw, and then dalnir, then kedge, then PoF, etc.<br><br>2. Know the zone and/or mob WELL.  If you are leading a raid, you should have been ON that particular raid (successful ones!) several times already, and been paying attention.  If it's your first time leading a particular raid (and often if it's not) you should have maps and guides with you at all times during the raid, and you should know them and consult them.  Having an experienced raid leader along or available for questions helps tremendously as well.<br><br>3. Ask for help if you need it.  If you are not a 100% confident, successful raidleader, ask for someone to help you lead.  Even if you ARE an experienced raid leader it makes things much easier to have someone splitting the responsibilities with you.  Also remember that there is more to being a raid leader than shouting orders -- that is not even the hardest part.  The &quot;behind the scenes&quot; work is just as important, so make sure it gets done and know that it is no less crucial to the success of a raid.<br><br>4. Plan in advance.  If it's going to be a large raid, make a post detailing all of your rules and policies (especially loot rules), what classes you need, how the roster will be chosen, etc.  You can look at any of my raid posts for examples of raid policies (not all raid leaders are that thorough, but I like to be very organized).  Especially important is making sure that loot rules are laid out clearly beforehand, to make sure there are no nasty situations or arguments later.<br><br>5. Put the raid on any applicable calendars.  Always put raids on our calendar (linked from the raids forum heading), and some raids can also be posted on the Lanys.com calendar (also linked from the raids forum heading).  If you're not sure which can be posted on Lanys, just ask.<br><br>6. Speaking of the Lanys.com calendar, I will go over the &quot;rules.&quot;  Raids may be posted no sooner than 2 weeks before the event and no later than 24 hours before it.  The calendar is NOT a reservation system and posting a raid in it by no means gives you exclusive rights to a zone.  It is a tool to let others know what your intentions are.  If someone else would like the same raid on the same day, they too can post and it is the responsibility of the two conflicting raid leaders to work out the time between themselves.  By the same token, if you would like to hold a raid on the same day that someone else has it calendared, post yours as well and contact the other raid leader to work something out.  Never, EVER use the calendar as an excuse to claim exclusive rights to something, be rude to someone else when you think they are &quot;running over your raid,&quot; or refuse to work with another raid leader respectfully when there is a conflict.  Guildies can click here to read a very old post I made about the calendar:<br><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://pub75.ezboard.com/ftrk72095frm2.showMessage?topicID=56.topic">pub75.ezboard.com/ftrk720...D=56.topic</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>(ignore all the junk in the rest of the thread, it was about something silly that happened a long time ago)<br><br>7. Make a roster a few days before the event.  Who you bring on a raid has a LOT to do with its success.  Allowing anyone and everyone in, unfortunately, can often lead to a mess, so be selective (not with guildies, of course, unless you have limited spaces).  If you are not sure about someone's reputation on raids, ask guildies or other raid leaders.  However it is NOT considerate to decide to exclude someone at the last minute -- make a roster and post it in advance so that if someone signed up but did not get in, they can make other plans.<br><br>8. Be online, at the gathering site, and preparing for the raid well in advance of the start time.  Make sure everyone has a ride who needs one.  Make sure you have all the necessary classes both before the raid and as it's starting -- no matter how much you stress to show up and be on time, there will be people who are late or just don't show.  Be prepared to send some tells and get some last minute replacements to keep the raid going.<br><br>9. If you made a roster, making groups will not be as difficult.  You should be able to use the basic groups you already made with a few modifications.  If you didn't, take time to make GOOD groups and announce them when it's time to get into groups.  Your first group should have a high level cleric, the main assist, the puller, the main enchanter, and a CoH'er if necessary (it goes without saying that you should make sure these first group people are competent!).  Other groups should be balanced with enough healing to take care of the damage group members will be taking, and so as not to have any one group so overpowered that it will take all the exp (although this usually happens no matter how hard you try :/).<br><br>10. Go over important things before the raid.  These will be different for each raid, so you might want to ask an experienced raid leader what kind of things to remind peeps about before the raid.<br><br>11. Assign someone to handle loot, someone who will do it quickly and fairly.  You will probably be too busy to handle that as well.  The person on loot should collect all money items, gems, and droppable loot for distribution at the end of the raid, and roll no-drop loot as soon as it drops.  You should ALWAYS make sure your clerics are compensated for gems, enchanters if runes are needed, mages for pearls, necros for coffins, etc.<br><br>12. Make sure the raid is moving along efficiently and that everyone is doing their jobs and following directions.  If someone is hindering the raid and/or not following instructions, you may have to TL him/her out for the good of the raid.  Always try to keep up with what is going on with the raid and stay in charge at all times.  If you are getting swamped in tells or cannot handle a situation, distribute responsibility or ask for help.  Often the biggest holdup on a raid is the raid leader him or herself -- make sure you are not holding the raid up because you are trying to take on too many things at once!<br><br>13. HAVE A CR PLAN!!  Wipeouts happen, no matter how good the raid is.  Have a plan to get the raid CR'ed and back on its feet at all times.  These will vary by zone, so ask if you need help forming one.<br><br>14. Stay positive no matter what happens.  Your attitude directly rubs off on your raiders, and if you let things get to you chances are good that the raid will not be successful or have a good time.  No matter how badly things go, do not get angry or upset while leading a raid!<br><br>15. When the raid is over, be sure you are the LAST person out.  Make sure everyone has gotten a ride out before you leave -- that is your responsibility.  If someone has gone LD, however, there is only so long you can wait for him/her. :/<br><br>16. Make sure everyone gets the loot they won, especially money items to compensate people who used components.  Sometimes this means you have to track people down after a raid, but again this is your responsibility!  <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub75.ezboard.com/ualundraadjani.showPublicProfile?language=EN>AlundraAdjani</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.theroyalknights.org/sigs/btnappheartred.gif" BORDER=0> at: 2/14/02 1:10:27 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CAD5D8><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub75.ezboard.com/ualundraadjani.showPublicProfile?language=EN>AlundraAdjani</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.theroyalknights.org/sigs/btnappheartred.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Saucy Phantasmist</span><br>  Posts: 3145<br> <font color=#33