t the line:<br>UseUmbra=FALSE<br>There are some who have bad connections or technical problems and cannot help going LD.  However a great many LDs are preventable, and they slow down and/or cause disaster for the raid.  Do your part to prevent them!<br><br>5. LISTEN.  If the raid leader is talking, be quiet.  Do not spam ooc, say, or especially shout.  Do not inundate the raid leader with tells.  Do not ask for buffs in public channels, but find out who is doing what buff and send that person a tell.  Chances are that if you were listening, you would know who was doing what buff, who the MA was, etc. already.<br><br>6. Get your buffs / buff your group. Don't wait to be told. If you don't know who's buffing, find out (not in public channels unless you cannot get an answer in group or tells).  When people die, they need re-buffing. It's not a surprise, so be ready to re-buff them and keep things moving forward quickly...even more so for &quot;key&quot; people like pullers, main chanta, so on.<br><br><br>7. ASSIST FOR THE LOVE OF GOD!!! :P  It's a simple concept that (IMO) ought to be tested just for a character to be able to hit level 50.  When the primary and secondary assists are called, make hotkeys RIGHT THEN.  Do NOT use any method of targetting besides your assist keys (unless you are a chanter, debuffer, etc.) and do NOT attack until you hear the assist message from the MA, even if that means not attacking for an entire fight.  It is better for NO damage to be done at all than for mezzes to be broken.<br><br>8. Please do not &quot;help&quot; the enchanters unless they ask for help (or doing the running around like a headless cheeken dance, which btw is also a license to tease us mercilessly about it later).  More often than not, this can end up making the situation worse instead of better.  I have had tanks who were attacking a mob to &quot;get it off me&quot; while I was repeatedly trying to mez it, and mez was breaking.  /cry  Do not be like this.  Chanters can usually handle themselves -- you do your job and let us do ours. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->      Note -- this does not apply to healers.  Feel free to heal a chanter all you want...I have been saved by my fair share of other groups' clerics seeing me getting beat on and helping to keep me alive. :P<br><br>9. Support and buffing classes should talk amongst themselves and distribute responsibilities if the raid leader does not do so, and let the raid know.  If you have a special job, like buffing, mezzing, pulling, etc., either do your job or ask the raid leader to assign it to someone else.  If you do not feel you can do an adequate job for whatever reason, or you have to leave, speak up and don't just let your job go undone!<br><br>10.  If you are a healer, make Hotkeys to /target the MA and SA.  If they are not in your group, preferably a few chanters as well, though the MA and SA are essential. If everything goes nuts, and depending on where you are raiding, it's not unusual for the MA's cleric to die. When this happens it's usually /shouted to heal the MA or SA. Rather then trying to mess around with typing /target MA, the hotkey helps a ton.<br><br>11. If a situation goes very bad and you hear the raid leader or another designated person shout &quot;CLERICS CAMP,&quot; that's what he/she means.  Really.  It means that if you are a cleric, camp, and if you are not a cleric DO NOT CAMP.  It means do not evac, gate, or anything else either!  It is your job to make sure the mobs stay off of the clerics so that they can get out alive, or else the CR will be very long and very nasty.<br><br>12. Do not whine or complain, especially about loot.  Even if it's just in your group.  If you don't like how a raid was run, don't go on any of that person's raids again.  If you have constructive criticism for the raidleader, tell him/her after the raid unless it's absolutely dire.  While you're on the raid, keep your whines and complaints to yourself!  And in line with that is...<br><br>13. Keep a good attitude.  Nothing ever goes perfectly, and rarely do things even go as planned.  There will be wipeouts, there will be unexpected situations, there will be bad loot days, and there will be inexperienced raid leaders.  But your main purpose is to have fun with your friends and guildies, and if you keep that in mind and keep a positive outlook, even the worst situation can turn into fun!<br><br>Edit: added suggestions. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub75.ezboard.com/ualundraadjani.showPublicProfile?language=EN>AlundraAdjani</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.theroyalknights.org/sigs/btnappheartred.gif" BORDER=0> at: 2/21/02 1:33:58 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CAD5D8><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub75.ezboard.com/ulashannavalrynn.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Lashanna Valrynn</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/white_star.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>The woman is right.</span><br>  Posts: 812<br> <font color=#333333>(2/14/02 9:15:20 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub75.ezboard.com/ftrk72095frm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=195.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://students.washington.edu/zip/eq/nicepika.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Raid attending guidelines</span><hr size=1> one thing to add for healers...<br><br>Make Hotkeys to /target the MA and SA if they are not in your group, preferably a few chanters as well, though the MA and SA are essential.  If everything goes nuts, and depending on where you are raiding, it's not unusual for the MA's cleric to die.  When this happens it's usually /shouted to heal the MA or SA.  Rather then trying to mess around with typing /target MA, the hotkey helps a ton. <p><center><img src="http://students.washington.edu/zip/eq/sig.jpg"></center></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CAD5D8><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub75.ezboard.com/uniblikvanduvere.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Niblik Vanduvere</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Stratman</span><br>  Posts: 388<br> <font color=#333333>(2/14/02 9:57:14 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub75.ezboard.com/ftrk72095frm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=195.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Raid attending guidelines</span><hr size=1> Addendums for all:<br>These helpful commands and settings have been known to make lag more bearable on raids:<br>/serverfilter on<br>/showspelleffects off<br>/shownames off (or /shownames 1)<br>/particle off <br>Chat filter - Set spells to group (or off/self)<br>Display - possibly turn sky off (instead of 1 layer/2 layer)<br>/targetgroupbuff on (if you have group buff spells to pass out)<br><br>For a more positive attitude:  when you go on any raid, expect to die a dozen times (and possibly lose level), receive no loot, and receive no compensation on any components.  This way your expectations are usually going to be set a lot lower than what -will- happen, thus making the raid more enjoyable for you <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br><br>Small tidbit to add for support crews...<br><br>If the raid leaders haven't pre-assigned tasks, this is a good way to figure out where you need to focus.  Some raid leaders have this already planned so you won't even need to do this -- but there aren't many raid leaders that are going to pre-assign tasks.<br><br>Start by using tells to discuss with those of your class what they wish to be doing.<br><br>Most enchanters are going to be discussing amongst themselves -through tells- about who is doing what buffs and the lead enchanter is usually the one to tell the raid leader that -- or the individual enchanters use the appropriate channel to inform the raiders (example:  use /ooc if /shout is being used for raid messaging).<br><br>Shamans may have a preference for what they wish to perform on a raid (like enchanters above)(Shaman01 does Str, Agi; Shaman02 does Dex, Sta; Shaman03 slows, etc.).  It helps a raid progress a lot if you discuss this with the other shamans (through tells, of course) while the raid is preparing to know who is going to do what tasks.  You can then inform the raid leader with a quick tell of:  shaman01 = str, agi; shaman02=dex, sta; shaman03=slows.  Also as above, you can use the &quot;off&quot; raid message channel to inform the raiders of the tasks you are performing (/ooc shaman02= dex, sta).<br><br>Most importantly, do NOT hog the raid channel and please don't spam.  If shout is being used to give instructions and key messages, do not start shouting spam (like songs).  Also, by spamming, you're keeping others from seeing instructions they may need. <p>Niblik Vanduvere - Proud to be a member of The Royal Knights - Epic Enchanter 55<BR>We control the Veritical...  We control the Horizontal...  Please do not adjust your sets!</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CAD5D8><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub75.ezboard.com/utistali0n.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Tistali0n</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>The Stallion</span><br>  Posts: 337<br> <font color=#333333>(2/15/02 12:01:40 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub75.ezboard.com/ftrk72095frm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=195.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Raid attending guidelines</span><hr size=1> Something I noticed some raids are good about and some are bad about ... and being good about this really makes things go _m